What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Its consisting of 113,937 values and 81 features. Some of them are loan features and in the type of categorical data (e.g. LoanStatus, IncomeRange, and Term) and others in form of quantitative data type (e.g. LoanOriginalAmount, and BorrowerRate)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My analysis will target Prospers Risk Rating Approach. I'll try to find out if this approach is efficient enough to detect and eliminate risks through the system and save investor money or it has some weak points. So, I'll consider classifying my interest features into two main groups:

  • $First$ one will be related to the loan itself, which is related to the investor as well, at which three of them are Categorical type (ProsperRiskRating, Term, and LoanStatus) and three are continuous quantitative type(BorrowerRate, LoanOriginalAmount, and MonthlyLoanPayment).

  • $Second$ one will be related to Borrower with the same schema of the first group, three categorical features (BorrowerState, EmploymentStatus, and IncomeRange) and three continuous quantitative (DebtToIncomeRatio, ProsperPrincipalBorrowed, and ProsperPrincipalOutstanding).

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Am sure that (LoanStatus) will be very important to spot if ,initially,(ProsperRiskRating) was accurate or not. Also, if (IncomeRange) was a tempting factor for better risk evaluation or not. Plus, do (BorrowerState, EmploymentStatus, and DebtToIncomeRatio) involved in the process or not. Moreover, what could be the relation between (Term, ProsperRiskRating, and BorrowerRate/LoanOriginalAmount).

- Investor (loan) features:¶
  • ProsperRiskRating ($AA_{Lowest} - A - B - C - D - E - HR_{Highest}$)
  • LoanStatus
  • Term
  • BorrowerRate
  • LoanOriginalAmount
  • MonthlyLoanPayment
- Borrower (consumer) features:¶
  • BorrowerState
  • EmploymentStatus
  • IncomeRange
  • DebtToIncomeRatio
  • ProsperPrincipalBorrowed (Total principal borrowed on Prosper loans at that time. If null,no prior loans.)
  • ProsperPrincipalOutstanding (Principal outstanding on Prosper loans at that time. If null,no prior loans.)

Pre-Exploration step:¶

Here I'll extract before mentioned features and look for / clean any Tidiness / Quality issues.

In [5]:
#Select specific columns to study 
selected_cols=['CreditGrade','ProsperRating (Alpha)','Term','LoanStatus','BorrowerRate','BorrowerState',
               'EmploymentStatus','DebtToIncomeRatio','IncomeRange','ProsperPrincipalBorrowed',
               'ProsperPrincipalOutstanding','LoanOriginalAmount','MonthlyLoanPayment']
df2= df.loc[:, selected_cols]
In [6]:
# Rename this column "ProsperRating (Alpha)" to "ProsperRatingAlpha" to be more consistent and easily in coding.
df2.rename(columns={'ProsperRating (Alpha)':'ProsperRatingAlpha'}, inplace=True)
In [7]:
# Columns "CreditGrade" and "ProsperRating (Alpha)" representing "Loan's Risk Rating" but each one for specific period of time.
# So, I'll combine them into one column "ProsperRiskRating" and drop the original two columns

df2['CreditGrade'].fillna("", inplace= True)
df2['ProsperRatingAlpha'].fillna("", inplace= True)

df2['ProsperRiskRating']= df2[['CreditGrade','ProsperRatingAlpha']].agg("".join, axis=1)
df2.drop(['CreditGrade', 'ProsperRatingAlpha'], axis=1, inplace=True)
In [8]:
# Rearrange data frame columns in specific shape
df2= df2.iloc[:, [11,1,0,2,9,10,3,4,6,5,7,8]]
In [9]:
# Drop Null values in "BorrowerState", "EmploymentStatus", and "DebtToIncomeRatio" only
df2.dropna(subset=['BorrowerState','EmploymentStatus','DebtToIncomeRatio'], inplace=True)
In [10]:
# Drop empty/null rows in "ProsperRiskRating" column
df2.drop(df2[df2['ProsperRiskRating'] == ""].index, inplace=True)
In [11]:
# Fill all Null value in "ProsperPrincipalBorrowed" with '0', as here null means that borrower has no historical loans
df2.ProsperPrincipalBorrowed.fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [12]:
# Fill all Null value in "ProsperPrincipalOutstanding" with '0', as here null means that borrower has no outstanding balance
df2.ProsperPrincipalOutstanding.fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [13]:
# Multiply all "BorrowerRate" values by 100 to easily interpreting in visualization
df2['BorrowerRate']= df2['BorrowerRate']*100
In [14]:
# Values in "DebtToIncomeRatio" are inconsistent, some in fracture format and others not. So, will multiply values <= 1 by 100 
df2['DebtToIncomeRatio']= df2['DebtToIncomeRatio'].apply(lambda x: x*100 if x <= 1 else x)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Regarding Prosper Principal Borrowed and Prosper Principal Outstanding, there is no identified distribution, but no need to transform them. Instead Debt To Income Ratio has the better distribution even it's skewed to the right.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Prosper Principal Borrowed and Prosper Principal Outstandingdistributions shows huge spike in one value "0", however, its still presenting useful isght reagrding its data.

I filtered out the columns of features of interest then made the following changes:

  • Rename this column "ProsperRating (Alpha)" to "ProsperRatingAlpha" to be more consistent and easily in coding.
  • Columns "CreditGrade" and "ProsperRating (Alpha)" representing "Loan Risk Rating" but each one for a specific period of time. So, I combined them into one column "ProsperRiskRating" and drop the original two columns.
  • Rearrange data frame columns in a specific shape to set each feature in alignment with its group of features (Investor, Borrower)
  • Drop Null values in "BorrowerState", "employment status", and "DebtToIncomeRatio" only to avoid these missing data affect in my analysis.
  • Drop null rows in the "ProsperRiskRating" column to not conflict with my categorical based analysis.
  • Fill all Null value in "ProsperPrincipalBorrowed" with '0', as here null means that borrower has no historical loans
  • Fill all Null value in "ProsperPrincipalOutstanding" with '0', as here null means that borrower has no outstanding balance
  • Values in "DebtToIncomeRatio" are inconsistent, some in fracture format and others not. So, will multiply values <= 1 by 100
  • Multiply all "BorrowerRate" values by 100 to easily interpreting in visualization

In [35]:
# Considering Defaulted and Chargedoff lonas as stopped/failed loans
sb.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(16,7)})
sb.set_style('darkgrid')

tmp= df2.query('LoanStatus == ["Defaulted","Chargedoff"]').groupby(['ProsperRiskRating','LoanStatus'])['Term'].count().reset_index()
tmp1= tmp.query('LoanStatus == "Chargedoff"').rename(columns={'Term':'Chargedoff'})
tmp1.drop('LoanStatus', axis=1, inplace=True)
tmp2= tmp.query('LoanStatus == "Defaulted"').rename(columns={'Term':'Defaulted'})
tmp2.drop('LoanStatus', axis=1, inplace=True)
tmp= pd.merge(tmp1, tmp2, left_on= 'ProsperRiskRating', right_on= 'ProsperRiskRating', how= 'inner').set_index('ProsperRiskRating').loc[['AA','A','B','C','D','E','HR'],:]
tmp['TotalLostLoans']= tmp['Chargedoff'] + tmp['Defaulted']
tmp= tmp.loc[:,['Defaulted','Chargedoff','TotalLostLoans']]

tmp.plot(kind='bar', width=.5, rot=0)

plt.legend()
plt.title('Number of failed loans for each risk class', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Prosper Risk Rating', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('Loan Count', fontsize=16);

Most of the non-committed cases related to the D risk class with the highest count of Chargedoff loans followed by the HR and C classes; it seems that many cases classified incorrectly. On the other hand, class AA showing the highest commitment amongst all other classes and with a considerable gap over the next risk level A.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • There is a consistent and very positive correlation between Loan Original Amount and Monthly Loan Payment.
  • Most of the non-committed cases related to the D risk class with the highest count of Charged-off loans followed by the HR and C class; it seems that many cases classified incorrectly.
  • Low-income range $1-24,999 has the highest Debt To Income Ratio that reaches almost 44%. Meanwhile, the higher-income range $100,000+reaches only 24%, almost half of the low-income class.
  • Both $25,000-49,999 and $50,000-74,999 ranges combined seized most of the loans in terms of Completed and Current loans.
  • As the income range goes high, the ratio of Completed and Current against each range total loans gets higher as well.
  • Regarding Average Debt to Income Ratio all states, mostly, swinging between 12% and 36%.
  • Lastly, most issues more probable to happen when the Average Debt to Income Ratio goes above 25%, even Charged-off and Past Due(31-60 days) cases happened when the rate was very close to 25%. While Completed loans have an average of almost 21%.
  • As the income range increase, total loans amount for each range increase which is related to the Debt To Income Ratio of each range.
  • Class A has loss rate less than class AA that almost equal to class B, while class H has the far highest rate 30%.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It seems that as the total borrowed amount increases, the probability of outstanding amount increases and reaches its highest peak at the value between 20k and 30k (within my data set).

Multivariate Exploration¶

Here, again, after testing/screening all my variables and all applicable interaction/relation between them I'll get back again to my analysis point "Do Prosper risk assessment approach captures and estimates each case risk efficiently and secures investors money?".

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • Generally Prosper Risk Assessment approach assigned gradually increased Rates for each risk class and the same for each Term within each class.
  • In total, income range$25,000-49,999 comes first as the worst performance and commitment regarding the total amount lost while range $50,000-74,999 comes in the second place. Meanwhile, income ranges $1-24,999 and $100,000+ are the best respectively
  • Finally, I can argue that Prosper Risk Assessment approach needs to manny adjustments to classify borrowers in the most appropriate class of risk to avoid the huge amount of money losses like that being in class D and C and don't count only on borrower rate as appeared here. As well, they should consider more the variable of Debt To Income ratio as a main eavaluationg factor in their classification as I noticed that some borrowers of class AA reached a ratio far higher than class HR.
